1042134443710971904.text: Learning like this means fewer comfy goal posts marking progress along the way. It means moving forward when things don't make sense, digging deeper in to confusion with the hope that you'll find light by breaking through the other side...

1042134441865474049.text: Following energy and passion instead of the "right" path as outlined by some educational authority seems like a faster way to learn, at least for me. What kept me away from this way? Well, it's incredibly uncomfortable to learn like this. It doesn't feel great...

1042134439759896576.text: Evidence from complexity theory, the @nntaleb books so in Vogue these days (do birds go to university to learn to fly?) and my own experience suggests that jumping from topic to topic and “linear” level to level (being a "sponge") can actually speed up learning...

1042134437339783168.text: But does the linear framework (drinking through a straw) actually work more effectively than the unconscious/non-linear? Or is it just more *comfortable*? That is the question I've been trying to answer recently...

1042134435364315138.text: Something I've recently noticed about my own efforts to learn - I continually fall back on linear learning approaches. I want to build from the first block to the second; skipping feels uncomfortable and disorienting...

1042134433485213698.text: This is how we learn consciously, but unconscious learning is often much less structured. Immersive Language learning is a good example - we pick up words and conventions here and there, making associations between them, until we can string sentences and meaning together...

1042134431081869312.text: We learn one thing, like addition, and then use that as a platform to learn another thing, like multiplication. Each lesson builds on the previous, implicitly (and occasionally explicitly) making "early" lessons a blocker for "later" lessons...

1042134429081235459.text: We start consciously learning. School is case in point - we receive lesson plans and intentionally push ourselves to "learn". The impact of the *style* in which we consciously learn is underappreciated. For example, most learning in school is linear...

973637396662124545.text: 11/11 What are your thoughts? Challenges are encouraged.

973637394078420993.text: 10/11 Our large minds allowed us to share myths and collaborate. By collaborating we now compete at an idea level rather than a genetic one. Progress skyrockets above purely evolution-driven progress. Compete with ideas (argue) rather than genes (kill).

973637392312672257.text: 9/11 This plays out in human history vs evolution as well. Evolution is a competitive system at the genetic level - selecting the best genes to move forward. Meanwhile, human progress has outpaced the increase in "fitness" via evolution over the past several thousand years.

973637390630756352.text: 8/11 also on contrary, pure competition at people level dis-incentivizes long term focus and the information sharing critical to learning. It also stamps out the potential impact of people who have good ideas or good execution but not both.

973637389041025025.text: 7/11 on contrary, collaboration at people level w/o idea competition tends towards consensus building where decisions are made based on people+interests involved rather than the merits of their ideas and execution.

973637387304579073.text: 6/11 Pushing competition to the level of the idea, rather than the individual, allows firm to get the best of both collaboration and competition and ditch downsides. Collaboration at people level means more ideas while retaining competition at idea level means better filters.

973637385354321920.text: 5/11 Amazon the company serves as a pool of talent that lowers the txn costs of finding people who come up with ideas and execute. Bridgewater is similar - culture looks kooky but serves to push competition to the level of the idea and it's execution.

973637383647256576.text: 4/11 The best companies know this intuitively and exhibit it in their operations and culture. Amazon is known as a marketplace of ideas where any idea with merit / that sticks will have weight put behind it to execute properly.

973637381969424384.text: 3/11 What these approaches miss is that progress comes not from competition at the firm or individual level, it comes from competition at the level of the idea and it's execution. (idea = strategies, tactics, + their execution) Companies and individuals are proxies for ideas.

973637380224634880.text: 2/11 The wisdom goes that competition is good for overall progress. At a markets level, this is seen as "firms competing produce better results than one company centrally planning". Some firms internalize this mindset, pitting individuals against one another for results

973637376038772736.text: 1/11 What people call "competitive" and "collaborative" have wildly different properties depending on the scale.
